Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A computer-implemented method for estimating tissue viability of patients' tissue, the method comprising: receiving a patient-specific vessel model or tissue model of a patient anatomy; receiving one or more patient-specific physiological parameters for one or more physiological states; estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific vessel model or target tissue model, using the patient-specific physiological parameters; and outputting the estimated characteristic of tissue viability to an electronic storage medium or display. 2. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the patient- specific physiological parameters may include an estimated or measured blood flow to a plurality of regions of the vessel or target tissue model at one or more physiological states. 3. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the patient- specific physiological parameters include one or more anatomical characteristics including, one or more of: vessel size, vessel shape, vessel tortuosity, vessel length, vessel thickness, or a combination thereof. 4. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the physiological states include, one or more of: a resting patient state, a hyperemic 

 state, an exercise state, a postprandial state, a gravitational state, an emotional state, a state of hypertension, a medicated state or a combination thereof. 5. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein a characteristic of tissue viability includes a measure of the extent to which a vessel, tissue, or organ is functional. 6. The computer implemented method of claim 5, wherein a characteristic of tissue viability further includes one or more of: fractional flow reserve, flow magnitude, flow direction, or a combination thereof. 7. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein: estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific vessel model or target tissue model includes using the received patient-specific physiological parameters and one or more image characteristics of a target tissue or a vessel in one or more physiological states, wherein the image characteristics includes, one or more of: local average intensities, texture characteristics, standard image features, characteristics related to an imaging or scanning modality, or a combination thereof. 8. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the patient- specific physiological parameters further include a plurality of secondary 

 characteristics including, one or more of: patient characteristics, target tissue disease characteristics, electromechanical measurements, or a combination thereof. 9. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific tissue or vessel model includes comparing the blood flow in the target tissue or vessel at one or more physiological states. 10. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the patient- specific vessel model and a patient-specific tissue mode! of a patient anatomy include, one or more of: a coronary vascular model and the myocardium; a cerebral vascular model and the brain; a peripheral vascular model and muscle; a hepatic vascular model and a liver; a renal vascular model and a kidney; a visceral vascular model and a bowel; or any target organ and vascular model with vessels supplying blood to said target organ. 11. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , further comprising: adjusting the patient-specific physiological parameters based on the estimated characteristics of tissue viability; and simulating a blood flow characteristic using the estimated characteristics of tissue viability and adjusted physiological parameters. 12. The computer implemented method of claim 1 , further comprising: changing one or more of the physiological parameters, patient-specific anatomical models, or image characteristics of the vessels or target tissue; and 

 generating a treatment recommendation based on the changed one or more of the physioiogical parameters, patient-specific anatomicai models, or image characteristics of the vessels or target tissue. 13. A system for estimating patient-specific tissue viability, the system comprising: a data storage device storing instructions for determining characteristics of tissue viability; and a processor configured to execute the instructions to perform a method including the steps of: receiving a patient-specific vessel model or tissue model of a patient anatomy; receiving one or more patient-specific physiological parameters for one or more physiological states; estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific vessel model or target tissue model, using the patient-specific physiological parameters; and outputting the estimated characteristic of tissue viability to a display. 14. The system of claim 13, wherein the patient-specific physiological parameters include, at one or more physiological states, one or more of the following: an estimated or measured blood flow to a plurality of regions of the vessel or tissue; anatomical characteristics; 

 patient characteristics; target tissue disease characteristics; electromechanical measurements; or a combination thereof . 15. The system of claim 13, wherein the physiological states include, one or more of: a resting patient state, a hyperemic state, an exercise state, a postprandial state, a gravitational state, an emotional state, a state of hypertension, a medicated state or a combination thereof. 16. The system of claim 13, wherein a characteristic of tissue viability includes a measure of the extent to which a vessel, tissue, or organ is functional. 17. The system of claim 16, wherein a characteristic of tissue viability further includes fractional flow reserve, flow magnitude, flow direction, or a combination thereof. 18. The system of claim 13, wherein estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific tissue or vessel model, includes comparing the blood flow in the target tissue or vessel at one or more physiological states. 19. The system of claim 13, wherein the patient-specific vessel model and a patient-specific tissue model of a patient anatomy include, one or more of: a coronary vascular model and the myocardium; a cerebral vascular model and the brain; a peripheral vascular model and muscle; a hepatic vascular model and a liver; 

 a renal vascular model and a kidney; a visceral vascular model and a bowel; or any target organ and vascular model with vessels supplying blood to said target organ. 20. A non-transitory computer readable medium for use on a computer system containing computer-executable programming instructions for estimating a characteristic of tissue viability, the method comprising: receiving a patient-specific vessel model or tissue model of a patient anatomy; receiving one or more patient-specific physiological parameters for one or more physiological states; estimating a characteristic of tissue viability of the patient-specific vessel model or target tissue model, using the patient-specific physiological parameters; and outputting the estimated characteristic of tissue viability to an electronic storage medium or display.
